# {{lb|en|botany}} One of the [[small]] [[drupelike|drupe-like]] [[subdivision]]s which [[compose]] the [[outer]] [[layer#Noun|layer]] of certain [[fruit#Noun|fruit]] such as [[blackberry|blackberries]] or [[raspberry|raspberries]]. {{defdate|from mid 19th c.}}
#: {{synonyms|en|drupel}}
#: {{ux|en|It is best to pick the berries while all '''drupelets''' are of a consistent, dark red coloration.}}
#: {{ux|en|The passengers on the chock-full boat were packed across the deck like '''drupelets'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Asa Gray|authorlink=Asa Gray|chapter=How Plants are Propagated or Multiplied in Numbers|title=Botany for Young People and Common Schools. How Plants Grow, a Simple Introduction to Structural Botany.{{nb...|With a Popular Flora, or an Arrangement and Description of Common Plants, both Wild and Cultivated. Illustrated by 500 Wood Engravings.}}|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Ivison, Blakeman, Taylor, & Co.|year=1858|section=section IV (Fruit and Seed), §&nbsp;1 (Seed-vessels), paragraph 244|page=81|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=excFAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA81|oclc=505717616|passage=''Aggregated Fruits'' are close clusters of simple fruits all of the same flower. The raspberry and blackberry are good examples. In these, each grain is a '''''drupelet''''' or stone-fruit, like a cherry or peach on a very small scale.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Asa Gray|authorlink=Asa Gray|chapter=Of the Fruit|title=Introduction to Structural and Systematic Botany, and Vegetable Physiology,{{nb...|being a Fifth and Revised Edition of The Botanical Text-book, Illustrated with over Thirteen Hundred Woodcuts.}}|edition=5th revised|location=New York, N.Y.; Chicago, Ill.|publisher=Ivison, Blakeman, Taylor, & Company,{{nb...|138 & 140 Grand Street. Chicago: 133 & 135 State Street.}}|year=1871|section=section II (The Kinds of Fruit), paragraph 600|page=313|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=nn4CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA313|oclc=18128009|passage=The raspberry and blackberry [...] are composed of a great number of miniature stone-fruits, or '''''drupelets''''', as they might be called, in structure resembling cherries [...], aggregated upon an elongated receptacle.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=A[lbert] S[pear] Hitchcock|authorlink=A. S. Hitchcock|chapter=Fruits and Seeds|title=Field Work for the Local Botanist|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Published by the author{{nb...|1867 Park Road, Washington, D.C.}}; composed and printed at the Waverley Press, Inc.{{nb...|Baltimore, Md., U.S.A.}}|year=1931|page=22|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=VE4XAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA4-PP26|oclc=1131468420|passage=The fruits of the genus Rubus (blackberry, raspberry) are aggregates of small drupes ('''drupelets''') upon the receptacle of a single flower, each '''drupelet''' from a single pistil.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Harold A. Kantrud|chapter=Development and Reproduction|title=Sago Pondweed (Potamogeton Pectinatus L.): A Literature Review|series=Fish and Wildlife Service Resource Publication|seriesvolume=176|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Fish and Wildlife Service|Fish and Wildlife Service]], {{w|United States Department of the Interior}}|year=1990|page=8|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9OCU3NLa9PsC&pg=RA6-PA8|column=2|issn=0163-4801|oclc=21504880|passage=In north temperate climates, the starchy '''drupelets''' of sago are usually mature by late July to late September. [...] Shortly after maturity, the '''drupelets''' fall to the bottom or float temporarily and wash ashore in windrows. [...] '''Drupelet''' germination occurs from late March to early summer in north temperate climates. '''Drupelets''' exposed for over a year on dry shorelines will germinate in as few as 4 days if wetted.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Helen J. Read|author2=Mark Frater|chapter=Management and Conservation|title=Woodland Habitats|series=Habitat Guides|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Routledge}}|year=1999|section=species box 3.2 (Bramble)|page=77|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=FoF7IfTQEXwC&pg=RA2-PA77|column=1|isbn=978-0-415-18089-4|passage=The berry is better known as the blackberry and, depending on the variety can have just a single '''druplet''' (seed surrounded by black flesh) or up to twenty '''druplets'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Stephen M. Ackerman|title=Raspberry Plant Named ‘PS-1764’|series=United States Plant Patent|seriesvolume=no. US PP15,439 P3|year=2003''' July 9 (filing date), '''2004''' December 21 (patent date)'''&#8203;|columns=2 and 3|columnurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=HkHwGjxd03MC&pg=PA10-IA6|passage=&#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=HkHwGjxd03MC&pg=PA10-IA6 column 2]&#93; This invention relates to a new and distinct everbearing variety of raspberry plant named 'PS-1764'. The new variety is primarily adapted to the growing conditions of the central coast of California and is characterized by the following. Fruit that is very large in size, light in color, glossy with very large '''druplets'''. [...] &#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=HkHwGjxd03MC&pg=PA10-IA7 column 3]&#93; 'PS-1764' fruit size, seed size and '''druplet''' size are much larger as compared to 'PS-127'.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Bernadine C. Strik|chapter=Growth and Development|editors=Harvey K. Hall and Richard C. Funt|title=Blackberries and Their Hybrids|series=Crop Production Science in Horticulture|seriesvolume=26|location=Wallingford, Oxfordshire; Boston, Mass.|publisher=[[w:Centre for Agriculture and Bioscience International|CABI]]|year=2017|page=29|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=OY1FDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA29|isbn=978-1-78064-668-8|passage=Each fertilized pistil/ovule will develop into a fleshy '''drupelet''' containing one seed  (a pyrene). Erect and semi-erect blackberry cultivars produce fruit with relatively large pyrenes compared to those of trailing blackberries.}}

